  "text": "Behavioral Performance before and after Numerosity Training In the color task, before numerosity training, color discrimination performance ( Figure 1C ) was well above chance for both monkeys (monkey L: 99.19% ± 0.24%; monkey S: 97.93% ± 0.34%; binomial test; p < 0.001) for all color combinations (as reported previously in [CITATION_1] ). We confirmed that none of the monkeys learned to judge numerosity in the color task by confronting the monkeys with colorless black dots. During the color task, numerosity performance tested on two sessions was at chance level for both monkeys (monkey L: 43.8% ± 12.7%; monkey S: 58.8% ± 12.4%; two-tailed binomial test; p > 0.05). This suggests that the monkeys were unable to use numerosity as discriminating stimulus feature during the color task.",
